THOUGHT: The program crashes with an AddressSanitizer double-free error. The sanitizer report shows that `free(b->name)` is called twice: once in `load_blob` when `strlen(name) > 4`, and again in `destroy_blob`. The root cause is that `load_blob` returns a partially initialized `blob_t` where `b->name` has been freed but `b` itself is still allocated and passed to `destroy_blob`. The `destroy_blob` function then attempts to free `b->name` again, causing the double-free. This happens because the function returns early after freeing `b->name`, but the caller still owns the `blob_t` struct and calls `destroy_blob`, which assumes `b->name` is valid.

The local fix is to ensure that `b->name` is not freed in `load_blob` if the caller will later destroy the blob. Instead, we should just set `b->name = NULL` and let `destroy_blob` handle the cleanup safely.

The global fix should enforce ownership semantics: either `load_blob` should return a fully initialized blob or it should not return a pointer at all. A better design would be to use a result type (e.g., `struct blob_result`) that explicitly encodes success/failure and ownership, or to use a RAII-style wrapper that ensures cleanup is only done once.

ROOT CAUSE: In `load_blob`, when `strlen(name) > 4`, the function frees `b->name` and returns the partially initialized `blob_t` struct, but the caller later calls `destroy_blob`, which attempts to free `b->name` again, causing a double-free. The function incorrectly assumes that the caller will not attempt to destroy the blob after a recoverable error, violating the invariant that `destroy_blob` should only be called on valid, owned blobs.

LOCAL FIX: Change the `load_blob` function to set `b->name = NULL` instead of freeing it on the recoverable error path, so that `destroy_blob` can safely handle it without double-freeing.

```c
if (strlen(name) > 4) {
    b->name = NULL;  // Do not free; let destroy_blob handle it safely
    b->size = 0;
    return b;
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Redesign `load_blob` to return a result type (e.g., `struct blob_result`) that encapsulates both success/failure and ownership, or use a RAII wrapper (e.g., a `blob_t *` that is only valid if `size > 0`) to prevent misuse. Alternatively, use a function that returns `NULL` on error and only returns valid pointers on success, ensuring that `destroy_blob` is only called on valid, owned blobs.

